AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background:¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective: To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.¶

Key Questions:¶

    1. How many different segments of customers are there?
    1. How are these segments different from each other?
    1. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description:¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre

Steps to follow:

    1. Perform univariate analysis on the data to better understand the variables at your disposal and to get an idea about the no of clusters.
    1. Perform EDA and take insights out. pts 1 and 2 – (5)
    1. Create visualizations to explore data and present the insights. (5)
    1. Properly comment on the codes and provide explanations of the steps taken in the notebook. (5)
    1. Execute hierarchical and K-means clustering (with different linkages) and do relevant visualisations (elbow plot, dendrograms etc) (10)
    1. Perform a silhouette analysis. (5)

def show_plots(df, features):
    for feature in features:
        print(f'***   {feature}      ***')
        print( df[feature].describe())
        fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (24, 6))
        sns.boxplot(df[feature], ax = ax1)
        plt.title(feature)
        if feature in [ 'Avg_Credit_Limit','Total_Credit']:
            sns.distplot(df[feature], kde = True, ax= ax2, rug=True)
            plt.axvline(df[feature].mean(),linestyle="dashed",label="mean")
            plt.legend(loc="best")
        else:
            sns.countplot(df[feature] ,ax= ax2)
        plt.title(feature)
        plt.show()
        yield

feature_analysis = iter(show_plots(cc_df,cols_numeric ))

def list_outliers(df, features):
    for feature in features:
        print(f'***   {feature}      ***')
        q1 = df[feature].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = df[feature].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = q3 - q1
        print( f'IQR: {IQR}')
        cdf = df[df[feature]> q3 + 1.5*IQR]
        print(cdf.describe())
        yield
cols_outliers  = ['Avg_Credit_Limit','Total_Credit','Total_visits_online']
list_outlier = iter(list_outliers(cc_df,cols_outliers ))

#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k ,random_state = 5)
    model.fit(scaled_df)
    prediction=model.predict(scaled_df)
    meanDistortions.append(model.inertia_)


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

In [29]:
def analyze_kmeans(k , label):
    global df_cluster
    print(f'******* k = {k}  Kmeans *******')
    
    final_model=KMeans(k, random_state =5)
    final_model.fit(scaled_df)
    prediction=final_model.predict(scaled_df)
    #Append the prediction 
    cc_df[label] = prediction
    cc_df[label] = cc_df[label].astype('category')
    
    # Silhoutte score
    score = silhouette_score(scaled_df, prediction)
    print(f'silhoutte score ={score:5.5f}')
    print()
    
    df_cluster=df_cluster.append({'type':'KMeans','number_clusters':k,'linkage':None,'silhoute_score':score
                       ,'inertia':final_model.inertia_,'cophenetic_index':None}, ignore_index = True)
    
    print(cc_df.groupby(by = label).mean().T)
    print()
    
    #Plots
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,4, figsize=(12,8) )
    sns.countplot(x = label , data = cc_df, ax = axs[0,0])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Avg_Credit_Limit', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[0,1])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_Credit_Cards', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[0,2])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_visits_bank', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[0,3])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_visits_online', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[1,0])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_calls_made', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[1,1])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_Credit', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[1,2])
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    return ( final_model , prediction )

In [34]:
def analyze_hierarchical(method , metric , y =None ):
    
    print(f'******* {method} {metric}   Dendogram *******')
    
    #dendogram
    Z = linkage(scaled_df, method=method , metric=metric)    
    c, _ = cophenet(Z , pdist(scaled_df))
    
    print(f'cophenet index ={c:5.5f}')
    print()
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.title('Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering Dendogram')
    plt.xlabel('sample index')
    plt.ylabel('Distance')
    dendrogram(Z,leaf_rotation=90.0,p=8,color_threshold=52,leaf_font_size=10,truncate_mode='lastp')
    if y is not None:
        plt.axhline(y=y, color='r', linestyle='--')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    return c

def analyze_hierarchical_model(k , label ,  affinity,  linkagex, cophenet):  
    global df_cluster
    final_model=AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=k, affinity=affinity,  linkage=linkagex)
    final_model.fit(scaled_df)
    prediction=final_model.labels_
    
    # Silhoutte score
    score = silhouette_score(scaled_df, prediction)
    print(f'silhoutte score ={score:5.5f}')
    print()
    
    df_cluster=df_cluster.append({'type':'Hierarchical','number_clusters':k,'linkage':linkagex,'silhoute_score':score
                       ,'inertia':None,'cophenetic_index':cophenet}, ignore_index = True)
    
    #Append the prediction 
    cc_df[label] = prediction
    cc_df[label] = cc_df[label].astype('category')
    print(cc_df.groupby(by = label).mean().T)
    print()
    #Plots
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,4, figsize=(12,8) )
    sns.countplot(x = label , data = cc_df, ax = axs[0,0])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Avg_Credit_Limit', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[0,1])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_Credit_Cards', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[0,2])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_visits_bank', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[0,3])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_visits_online', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[1,0])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_calls_made', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[1,1])
    sns.boxplot( y = 'Total_Credit', x = label , data = cc_df , ax = axs[1,2])
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    #return ( final_model , prediction ,score )

It is obvious from the above comparision that both Hierarchial and Kmeans are able to cluster the customers into 3 different groups :¶

  • Group 1 [2 in KNN, 1 in Hierarchial]

High Credit limit, Many Cards , Interact Online only

  • Group 2 [ 0 in KNN , 2 in Hierarchial ]

Low Credit Limit , Few Credit Cards , They mostly interact through phone but also prefer online

  • Group 3 [ 1 in KNN , 0 in Hierarchial ]

Medium Credit Limit , Few Credit Cards , Visit Banks more ofthen than others, hardly use online

Recommendation:

  • If the Bank wants to get customers with High Credit , it needs to make online service better

  • Making online better will also help the Low Credit Customers as they also use online ( second preference as compaired to telephone)

  • The Medium Credit Customers are the customers who come to the bank most. They hardly use online. This can also mean that the features they need are not avaiable online. The Bank has most of its customers in Low and Medium credit. There has to be a reason why Medium credit customers have to come to the bank while the low credit can use both phone or online.

Improving online service will positively impact everyone. Its seems right now online is focussed only to tthe experience/needs of high credit
